summary.seg: This small manuscript contains a Nomocanon in 220 chapters. The Nomocanon is a collection of ecclesiastical regulations (canons) and civil laws relating to ecclesiastical matters.
The manuscript was written by a single scribe, who notes that this copy was completed in the year 1669.

support.material:
ff. 1-126 Western paper, folded in octavo.
Watermarks: there are traces of watermarks near the upper or lower edge, near the gutter (and a countermark with letters and a clover in the centre of the leaf), but it was not possible to identify them.

supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil, in Arabic numerals, in the upper margin, right: 1-126.

collation.p: The codex is formed of quires of 14, 16 and 18 leaves.
collation.catchwords: Vertical catchwords by the scribe on the verso of each leaf.

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript is in poor condition. The binding is damaged: both boards are lost, only the spine remains, the manuscript is preserved in a box. F. 1 is damaged, the ink has partially faded, there are tears, and a part of the leaf is missing. There are humidity and water stains throughout.

list.item: ff. 1r-24v: a single column of 19-20 lines
ff. 25r-31v: a single column of 14 lines
ff. 32r-107v: a single column of 13 lines
ff. 108r-126v: a single column of 21 lines

handNote.p: ff. 1r-126v Hand A: a minuscule script slanting to the right, flowing, characterized by hooks at the ends of strokes, and a tendency to prefer angular forms. Uprights are always curved and tend to be oblique.

decoDesc.decoNote: On f. 1r there is a rectangular headpiece traced in brown ink; in the centre there is a plaited motif on a black background; the headpiece has a red frame.

Friezes are present throughout:
f. 2r, 10r frieze representing a branch with leaves, traced in black ink with some elements coloured in red
f. 14v rope motif, traced in black ink, partially filled in red
ff. f. 114v, 117r friezes representing a branch, with knots, traced in black ink with a red line within
f. 126r frieze representing a branch traced in red ink.

decoNote.p: Initials in ekthesis in red ink decorated with vegetal motifs, see e.g. ff. 1r and 114v.
Minor initials in red ink, sometimes with small decoration, see e.g. ff. 113r and 113v.
Zoomorphic initials in red ink (fishes), see e.g. ff. 105v and 108v.

additions.p: On f. 1r is written, in black ink, the shelfmark Add. 3050.
In the lower margin of f. 126v is written a number, by a later hand; the ink is faded, possibly 1828 (a date?).

binding.p: Both boards have been lost, only the spine remains. It belonged to a western binding, and it is covered in brown leather with blind tooling in form of two flowers and a star. The manuscript is preserved in a box made by Wilson and son with gold tooled shelfmark. With the manuscript is kept a leaf of paper which was folded and used as a paper wrapper for the manuscript (see Accompanying Material).

accMat.p: In the box, with the manuscript, is kept a small folder containing some soft material (perhaps wool), which was inserted at f. 79.

With the manuscript comes, in a paper folder, a leaf ( 222 320 ), in western paper (no watermark is visible), which now has been sealed in a melinex envelope. Shadings and stains on the leaf suggest that it was once used as a wrapper for the manuscript: in the upper part, centre, there is a water stain, which corresponds with a similar stain in the upper part of the external leaves of the manuscript (see f. 1r), near the gutter. On the leaf there are handwritten notes in black ink: accounts, calculations, and some notes written in a late Greek hand, in modern Greek. The notes were written before the leaf was folded.

origin.p: The manuscript was written in 1669, as the colophon on f. 114r states.

history.provenance: Owned by C. J. Cummings Cummings, C. J. of Volo.
history.acquisition: Bought by Cambridge University Library from Cummings in 1892 through H. C. Rae Rae, H. C. of Liverpool.

recordHist.source: Description (2021) draws partly on P. Easterling, 'Hand-list of the additional Greek manuscripts in the University Library, Cambridge', in: Scriptorium 16 (1962), pp. 302-323: 319.
